    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">
        <p class="lede-p"><strong>Anyword is the only AI copywriting tool that genuinely predicts performance.</strong> It is also the wrong tool for almost any SEO content workflow. After 21 days of A/B testing across Meta Ads, Google Ads, and email subject lines — with 600+ paid impressions to validate the Predictive Score — here is the honest verdict, the real situations where the score actually moves CTR, and the seven cases where Anyword is the right call.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Editorial disclosure</div>
          <p>This review was written and published by theStacc, a competing product in the content space (we serve SEO; Anyword serves performance marketing). We have a commercial interest as an alternative. Every feature claim and price was verified against Anyword's public pricing page as of Q2 2026.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-tldr">
          <div class="callout-label">⚡ TL;DR — The 30-second verdict</div>
          <p><strong>Buy Anyword if</strong> you run paid ads (Meta, Google, LinkedIn) or send transactional + marketing emails at volume — the Predictive Score genuinely moves CTR. The Data-Driven plan at $79/mo is the sweet spot. <strong>Skip Anyword if</strong> your job is SEO content, blog publishing, or organic traffic — wrong tool, the score is calibrated for ad clicks, not search rankings. If you want organic traffic, theStacc handles content + publishing from $99/mo.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="inline-cta">
